<br>
To be alive is to smell the aromatic blossom on trees fresh from a hard bitter winter. The gentle touch of anothers lips upon your own.<br>
<br>
Death is a place in which the soul departs the body it once used in an attempt to change some small thread of history. <br>
<br>
Good is what a Samaritan is called, but what is a Samaritan? <br>
<br>
A man who finds a child lost in a crowded market and leads her home? A hunter who swiftly kills his prey snared in his trap all night? Someone who finds a traveller bleeding and half dead by a roadside, knowing he will not survive much longer but in excruciating pain he brings death quicker with the thrust of a sword? Surely then he could also be labelled as  bad for committing a murder?<br>
<br>
So is bad a term for a mischievous errand boy who sticks out his tongue rudely at a passing noble then makes haste for the protection of a crowded market place? A thief who robs from those who have more than he to feed his starving family? Or a man who would kill for the love and revenge of a woman scorned ?<br>
<br>
Are you rich if you have all the wealth a person could need in gold and luxuries? <br>
<br>
So then a man who has little but a roof over his head, a loving wife and healthy family, is poor or is he in some ways richer than the noble who wants for nothing material? <br>
<br>
These questions are asked many times by people, several times in a day.<br>
<br>
I know that just as I stare down at you sleeping so soundly, you too will ask these questions of yourself and the world you live in, not too far in the future. I wonder if it is right for me now to go forth with my challenge and leave you here, vulnerable as a newly hatched chick on the ground with a wolf’s den next to you. A sigh is all I can manage again. It pains me to know I must use this memorystone and hope someday it will reveal all of your mother and myself to you....<br>
 <p><center><b><u><font color=#0000ff>Alvar Coldraven</font></u></b> 
